A/B Testing Introduction

A/B testing started as comparison of 2 features, but now it includes multivariate cases as well. Although some people distinguish A/B testing as testing one feature against all and multivariate testing as testing a few equally important features at once.

A conversion occurs when a visitor to your website completes a desired goal, such as filling out a form or making a purchase. The percentage of total visitors that convert is called your conversion rate. It could be called click-through-rate and return on investment.)

A/B Testing Applications

  • Email subject lines: Test different subject lines to increase your open rates.
  • Calls-to-action: Which version boosts conversions ?
  • Layouts, Colors, Fonts, Content length: Changing any can help or decrease rates.
  • Navigation: Test different types of navigation to determine how users prefer to interact with your website.
  • Images: Choosing logo or ad photo can be optimized instead of guessing.
  • Market segmentation
  • Many others: Direct mailings, billboards, TV commercials, business cards, radio spots and so on.

Data Size Restriction Problems

A general advice is to get at least 1000 page visitors and to gather data for at least a week. But we do not know would it suffice or not. Our aim is to get 97-99% statistical significance, but there are a lot of things in a way.

  • Business demands
  • Gathering data can be costly.
  • Conditions may change quicker than data are collecting.
  • Imbalanced data
  • Technical difficulties
  • Legal requirements

A Considered Example

For this particular presentation I will consider a few ads which are supposed to be displayed on a web page. We want to determine an ad which gets the most clicks.

A Problem Set up

  • There is a paid spot on a website where we are to display one image.
  • We have 6 images with control to display one of them when a visitor opens a website.
  • We compute conversion rate means and estimate their possible error margins.

One of the methods for possible error margin estimations is a confidence interval.

A confidence interval definition

A confidence interval (the definintion is from Wiki)

A confidence interval (CI) is a type of interval estimate (of a population parameter) that is computed from the observed data. The confidence level is the frequency (i.e., the proportion) of possible confidence intervals that contain the true value of their corresponding parameter. In other words, if confidence intervals are constructed using a given confidence level in an infinite number of independent experiments, the proportion of those intervals that contain the true value of the parameter will match the confidence level.

Evaluations

  • Traditional statistical methods: using formulas for CI bounds, for example: \( 1.96\sqrt{p(1-p)/N} \), or more refined one: \( \sqrt{(3 \log (n) /(2 N))} \) (level = 0.95)
  • Empirical evaluations: using bootstrapping to generate possible means, then calculating CI using quantile computations.

Optimization for particular goals

If we have a particular goal in mind we may be able

to adjust our data collection to optimize it.

A Multi-bandit approach

The idea behind the Multi-bandit approach is to adjust our ad displays using our results so far to optimize our goal, so we can get more from less.

Let us assume that in this particular case we want to know what rate is the greatest and we would like to reduce amount of time (and money) on ads which do not perform well.

Multi-bandit methods

  • Initial “Naive” methods
  • \( \epsilon \)-Greedy
  • Upper Confidence Bound
  • Thompson Sampling Method
  • there modifications and others

Epsilon Greedy

  • Pick up \( \epsilon \) such that 0 ≤ \( \epsilon \) ≤ 1 (often 0.01 or 0.1)
    and number N of initial trials
  • Run N trials and find an ad with a highest average reward at this point.
  • At each next trial, identify the ad with the best average reward and use 1-\( \epsilon \) of the time.
  • For the other \( \epsilon \) fraction of runs, pick another ad randomly.

Remark 1. The method is easy to understand and to implement, but it is not very efficient.

Remark 2. It works for any statistic.

(I did not make any graphs or video for the method.)

Upper Confidence Bound (UCB)

At each step:

  • Compute mean rewards for each conversion rate at this point.

  • Calculate for them CI upper bounds (UCB).

  • Pick the ad with the highest UCB for our next display.

  • Go back to first step.

Upper Confidence Bound (UCB) method

Remark 1. There are different formulas for UCB computations, but in the long run they come to the same result.

Remark 2. The method can be adapted for another statistic we want to optimize as long as we know how to compute a good CI for it.

Remark 3. If we added another ad after the trials starts then it may mess up our results.

Remark 4. We can compute empirical intervals using bootstrapping, although it takes more computer resources.

Thompson Sampling method

  • Use Beta distributions as approximate conversion rate distribution functions.

  • Compute \( \alpha \) and \( \beta \) parameters for each of them.

  • Sample a corresponding random number from each resulting Beta distribution

  • Pick the highest and choose the corresponding ad for next display.

Thompson Sampling method

Remark 1. The method converges a bit quicker and even more easily accommodates an ad added after start of trials.

Remark 2. It may be difficult to adapt it for another statistic we want to optimize.

Remark 3. We can sample a random number from empirical distributions using bootstrapping, although it takes more computer resources.
